{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:26:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:26:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17877"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17877"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10591"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78732"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10591"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17877"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8761"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24689"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with severe malnutrition following prolonged critical illness. She has been receiving parenteral nutrition without glutamine supplementation. On examination, she appears cachectic with a body mass index of 16 kg/m2. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Blood tests reveal low serum protein and albumin levels. There is evidence of increased intestinal permeability on specialised testing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the preferred substrate for intestinal epithelial cell metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glutamate","Glucose","Glutamine","Glutathione","Methionine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of glutamine in intestinal function. \u003Cstrong\u003EGlutamine\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred substrate for intestinal epithelial cell metabolism. It serves as a critical energy source and is essential for maintaining the integrity and function of the intestinal barrier. Glutamine is rapidly metabolised by enterocytes, the cells lining the intestine, and supports their growth and repair. In critical illness, glutamine requirements increase significantly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlutamate\u003C/strong\u003E is another amino acid that can be used by intestinal cells, but it is not the primary substrate for energy metabolism. While it plays a role in various cellular processes, it does not match glutamine\u0027s importance in intestinal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E is a common energy source for many cells in the body, but intestinal epithelial cells preferentially use glutamine over glucose for their metabolic needs. This preference reflects the unique metabolic requirements of the intestinal epithelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlutathione\u003C/strong\u003E is an important antioxidant in the body, but it is not a primary energy substrate for intestinal epithelial cells. Its main role is in protecting cells from oxidative stress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethionine\u003C/strong\u003E is an essential amino acid involved in various metabolic processes, but it is not the preferred substrate for intestinal epithelial cell metabolism. While important for protein synthesis, it does not serve as a primary energy source for enterocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glutamine is the preferred substrate for intestinal epithelial cell metabolism.","Intestinal epithelial cells rely on glutamine for energy and cellular function.","Glutamine supports the integrity and function of the intestinal barrier."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Rath E, Haller D. Intestinal epithelial cell metabolism at the interface of microbial dysbiosis and tissue injury. Mucosal Immunol. 2022 Apr;15(4):595-604. doi: 10.1038/s41385-022-00514-x. Epub 2022 May 9. PMID: 35534699; PMCID: PMC9259489.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty acid metabolism: target for metabolic syndrome. J Lipid Res. 2009 Apr;50 Suppl(Suppl):S138-43. doi: 10.1194/jlr.R800079-JLR200. Epub 2008 Dec 1. PMID: 19047759; PMCID: PMC2674721"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17877"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T15:50:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T15:52:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10591"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78732"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"upda